description: Test questions covering programming concepts, algorithms, and code understanding

questions.question: What does HTML stand for?
questions.expected_answer: HyperText Markup Language

questions.question: What is the time complexity of binary search?
questions.expected_answer: O(log n)

questions.question: What is a for loop used for in programming?
questions.expected_answer: Iterating over a sequence or repeating code a specific number of times

questions.question: What is the difference between == and === in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: == checks for equality with type coercion, === checks for equality without type coercion

questions.question: What is recursion?
questions.expected_answer: A function that calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it into smaller subproblems

questions.question: What does SQL stand for?
questions.expected_answer: Structured Query Language

questions.question: What is the purpose of a constructor in OOP?
questions.expected_answer: To initialize objects when they are created

questions.question: What is the output of print(2 ** 3) in Python?
What is a REST API?
questions.expected_answer: An API that follows REST architectural style using HTTP methods for CRUD operations

questions.question: What data structure uses LIFO?
questions.expected_answer: Stack

questions.question: What does OOP stand for?
questions.expected_answer: Object-Oriented Programming

questions.question: What is Big O notation used for?
questions.expected_answer: To describe the time or space complexity of algorithms

questions.question: What does the keyword 'this' refer to in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: The current object context

questions.question: What is a hash table?
questions.expected_answer: A data structure that maps keys to values using a hash function

questions.question: What is the purpose of git?
questions.expected_answer: Version control system for tracking changes in code

questions.question: What is a binary tree?
questions.expected_answer: A tree data structure where each node has at most two children

questions.question: What does JSON stand for?
questions.expected_answer: JavaScript Object Notation

questions.question: What is polymorphism in OOP?
questions.expected_answer: The ability of different classes to respond to the same method call in different ways

questions.question: What is the difference between a compiler and an interpreter?
questions.expected_answer: Compiler translates entire program at once; interpreter executes line by line

questions.question: What does CSS stand for?
questions.expected_answer: Cascading Style Sheets

questions.question: What is a linked list?
questions.expected_answer: A data structure where elements are stored in nodes, each pointing to the next node

questions.question: What is the purpose of a foreign key in databases?
questions.expected_answer: To establish and enforce a link between two tables

questions.question: What is the difference between var, let, and const in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: var is function-scoped, let/const are block-scoped, const cannot be reassigned

questions.question: What is encapsulation in OOP?
questions.expected_answer: Bundling data and methods that operate on that data within a single unit or class

questions.question: What does HTTP stand for?
questions.expected_answer: HyperText Transfer Protocol

questions.question: What is a queue data structure?
questions.expected_answer: A FIFO (First-In-First-Out) data structure

questions.question: What is the purpose of an index in a database?
questions.expected_answer: To improve the speed of data retrieval operations

questions.question: What is the time complexity of quicksort on average?
questions.expected_answer: O(n log n)

questions.question: What is inheritance in OOP?
questions.expected_answer: A mechanism where a new class derives properties and methods from an existing class

questions.question: What is an API?
questions.expected_answer: Application Programming Interface - a set of rules for building and interacting with software

questions.question: What is a graph in data structures?
questions.expected_answer: A collection of nodes (vertices) connected by edges

questions.question: What is normalization in databases?
questions.expected_answer: Organizing data to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity

questions.question: What is async/await in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: A way to handle asynchronous operations using promises with cleaner syntax

questions.question: What is a callback function?
questions.expected_answer: A function passed as an argument to another function to be executed later

questions.question: What does DOM stand for?
questions.expected_answer: Document Object Model

questions.question: What is dynamic programming?
questions.expected_answer: An optimization technique that solves complex problems by breaking them into simpler subproblems and storing results

questions.question: What is the difference between  SQL and NoSQL?
questions.expected_answer: SQL uses relational tables with fixed schemas; NoSQL uses flexible, non-relational data models

questions.question: What is a closure in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: A function that has access to variables in its outer (enclosing) function scope

questions.question: What is abstraction in OOP?
questions.expected_answer: Hiding complex implementation details and showing only essential features

questions.question: What is CRUD?
questions.expected_answer: Create, Read, Update, Delete - basic operations for persistent storage

questions.question: What is a heap data structure?
questions.expected_answer: A complete binary tree where each node satisfies the heap property (min-heap or max-heap)

questions.question: What is the difference between GET and POST HTTP methods?
questions.expected_answer: GET retrieves data (parameters in URL); POST sends data (parameters in body)

questions.question: What is a promise in JavaScript?
questions.expected_answer: An object representing the eventual completion or failure of an asynchronous operation

questions.question: What is depth-first search (DFS)?
questions.expected_answer: A graph traversal algorithm that explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking

questions.question: What is a primary key?
questions.expected_answer: A unique identifier for a record in a database table

questions.question: What is the virtual DOM in React?
questions.expected_answer: A lightweight copy of the actual DOM used for efficient updates

questions.question: What is memoization?
questions.expected_answer: An optimization technique that stores the results of expensive function calls and returns cached result when same inputs occur

questions.question: What is the difference between a class and an object?
questions.expected_answer: A class is a blueprint/template; an object is an instance of a class

questions.question: What is a RESTful service?
questions.expected_answer: A web service that follows REST principles using HTTP methods and stateless communication

questions.question: What is the space complexity of an algorithm?
questions.expected_answer: The amount of memory space required by an algorithm relative to input size
